07459nam a22010935i 9789048536818DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485368187 a10.1515/97890485368182doi  a(DE-B1597)550717  a(OCoLC)1157344841  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aBUS1000002bisacsh04a95104aThe Heritage Turn in China :bThe Reinvention, Dissemination and Consumption of Heritage /ced. by Yi-Wen Wang, Linda Walton, Carol Ludwig. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (314 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsian Heritages ;v500tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tSection 1. (Re)constructions, (Re)inventions, and Representations of Heritage -- t1 The Social Life of Heritage-Making -- t2 Confucian Academies and the Materialisation of Cultural Heritage -- t3 From Destruction to Reconstruction -- t4 Set in Stone -- tSection 2. Creating Identities: Constructing Pasts, Disseminating Heritage -- t5 Contemporary Fabrication of Pasts and the Creation of New Identities? -- t6 Creating Cultural Identity in China -- t7 The Museum as Expression of Local Identity and Place -- tSection 3. History, Nostalgia, and Heritage: Urban and Rural -- t8 The Role of History, Nostalgia and Heritage in the Construction and Indigenisation of State-led Political and Economic Identities in Contemporary China -- t9 Local Voices and New Narratives in Xinye Village -- tSection 4. Appropriations and Commodifications of Ethnic Heritage -- t10 'Even If You Don't Want to Drink, You Still Have to Drink' -- t11 'Ethnic Heritage' on the New Frontier -- tAfterword -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis edited volume focuses on heritage discourse and practice in China today as it has evolved from the 'heritage turn' that can be dated to the 1990s. Using a variety of disciplinary approaches to regionally and topically diverse case studies, the contributors to this volume show how particular versions of the past are selected, (re)invented, disseminated and consumed for contemporary purposes. These studies explore how the Chinese state utilises heritage not only for tourism, entertainment, educational and commercial purposes, but also as part of broader political strategies on both the national and international stage. Together, they argue that the Chinese state employs modes of heritage governance to construct new modernities while strengthening collective national identity in support of both its political legitimacy and its claim to status as an international superpower. The authors also consider ways in which state management of heritage is contested by some stakeholders whose embrace of heritage has a different purpose and meaning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCultural propertyzChina. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aHeritage Studies. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 4aPolitics and Government. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Museum Administration & Museology.2bisacsh  aCultural heritage, heritage conservation, identity, nationalism, soft power.1 aBayer, Kristin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Melissa Shani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraezer Bideau, Florence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuo, Yingjie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaw, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawson, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLudwig